{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535455"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:56:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:56:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15457"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.07,0.11,0.02,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89943"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8148"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74102"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40325"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of painless haematuria. He has worked in a rubber manufacturing plant for the past 30 years. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is an ex-smoker with a 20 pack-year history, having quit 10 years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals no masses or tenderness. Urinalysis confirms frank haematuria with no evidence of infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative occupational exposure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnesium","Asbestos fibres","Silica dust","Wood dust","2-naphthylamine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with haematuria and has a significant occupational history working in the rubber manufacturing industry. The combination of these factors strongly suggests occupational bladder cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2-naphthylamine\u003C/strong\u003E is an aromatic amine that was commonly used in the rubber industry and is a known bladder carcinogen. Workers exposed to this chemical have a significantly increased risk of developing bladder cancer, with latency periods often exceeding 20 years after initial exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsbestos fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily associated with mesothelioma and lung cancer, not bladder cancer. Exposure typically occurs in construction, shipbuilding, and insulation work.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium\u003C/strong\u003E is not a known carcinogen and is not associated with bladder cancer. It is an essential mineral used in various industrial processes but does not pose the same occupational hazards as aromatic amines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilica dust\u003C/strong\u003E exposure primarily causes silicosis and increases the risk of lung cancer. It is commonly encountered in mining, construction, and sandblasting operations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWood dust\u003C/strong\u003E exposure is associated with sinonasal cancers and nasopharyngeal carcinoma, particularly in furniture makers and carpenters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther aromatic amines associated with bladder cancer include benzidine and 4-aminobiphenyl. These compounds were widely used in the dye industry before their carcinogenic properties were recognised. The combination of occupational exposure and smoking (even in ex-smokers) has a multiplicative effect on bladder cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Occupational exposure to aromatic amines is a significant risk factor for bladder cancer, particularly in workers in the rubber, dye, and chemical industries.","Haematuria is the most common presenting symptom of bladder cancer and requires urgent investigation.","A detailed occupational history is essential when evaluating patients with haematuria or bladder cancer."],"references":["2-Naphthylamine (IARC Summary \u0026 Evaluation, Supplement7, 1987) [Internet]. Inchem.org. 2024 [cited 2024 Nov 15]. Available at: https://inchem.org/documents/iarc/suppl7/naphthylamine2.html","\u200cAn Updated Review of the Literature: Risk Factors for Bladder Cancer with Focus on Occupational Exposures [Internet]. Sma.org. 2014 [cited 2024 Nov 15]. Available at: https://sma.org/southern-medical-journal/article/an-updated-review-of-the-literature-risk-factors-for-bladder-cancer-with-focus-on-occupational-exposures/\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74102"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74102"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T14:25:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T20:24:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8148"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id"